                    ### [Enchantments](id:enchantments)

                    Items and armor can have custom enchantments by using the `enchantment` attribute. Enchantments are specified by their bukkit name and the enchantment level separated by a colon `:`. Multiple enchantments are separated by a semicolon `;`.

                    Examples

                        <item enchantment="damage all:2">iron sword</item> <!-- A sharpness II iron sword -->
                        <item enchantment="knockback:4">280</item> <!-- A knockback IV stick -->

                        <boots enchantment="protection fall:2">gold boots</boots>

                    <br/>
                    ### [Attributes](id:attributes)

                    The `attributes` attribute will allow you to set the attribute('s) for a item or a piece of armor. Look at the [attributes reference](/reference/attributes) page for a list of the different attributes. The attribute definition is separated by colons `:`, and consists of the attributes name, operation and level. Multiple attributes are separated by a semicolon `;`.

                    **Attribute Operations:**

                    * `ADD` Add level to original level value.
                    * `BASE` Add level * base to original level value.
                    * `MULTIPLY` Multiply original level value by level.

                    <br/>
                    Examples

                        <chestplate attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1">chainmail chestplate</chestplate>

                        <item attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1">diamond spade</item>
                        <item attributes="generic.knockbackResistance:add:1;generic.movementSpeed:add:2">diamond spade</item>

                        <!-- Unit of maxHealth is in half-hearts -->
                        <leggings attributes="generic.maxHealth:add:-6">iron leggings</leggings>

                    `NOTE:` Negative attribute values are allowed; however sometimes they don't work as expected.

                    <br/>
                    ### [Grenades](id:grenades)

                    The `grenade="true"` attribute will make the item explode on impact, just like a grenade. This option only works on items that can turn into projectiles. For example, ender pearls, snowballs, eggs, and arrows all work.

                    The `grenade-power="1.0"` attribute sets the explosion power. The default value of `1.0` will not destroy blocks, but it will damage players and set off TNT.

                    The attributes `grenade-fire="true"` and `grenade-destroy="true"` determine if the explosion creates fire and/or destroys blocks.

                    `NOTE:` If an ender pearl is used as a grenade, the player will teleport to the location and the explosion will occur.


                        <item slot="1" amount="12" name="`4Grenade" grenade="true" grenade-power="1.2">snow ball</item>
                        <item name="`a`lRocket Ammo" amount="3" enchantment="thorns" grenade="true" grenade-power="4" grenade-fire="true">arrow</item>
